column1: iâ€™ve actively been trying to heal myself from past trauma. whenever it arises
column2: iâ€™ve honor those feelings by sitting with them
column3: asking why they exist and in some cases
column4: sharing them on here with yâ€™all to hold myself accountable in this journey and to show you a healing process of one survivor. itâ€™s never a straight line forward or through.

column2: i did a journaling exercise that highlighted my comfort zones
column3: my attachments to things that make me feel secure. our comfort zones in our career
column5: personal lives are what keeps us surrounded by the familiar
column6: by feelings of warmth and safety
column7: but limit our growth. and when we chase growth too much
column8: we often abandon the belief that we are enough simply as we are. finding the balance of two is the crossroads we find ourselves at often.

column1: vulnerability hour ğŸ‘‰ğŸ¼ i recently signed back up for the dating apps for that part of my life feels ready to reopen (slowly). in doing so
column2: iâ€™m starting to really see the comfort zones iâ€™ve created for my romantic life as a rape survivor. rightfully so... iâ€™ve felt a level of hurt that i hope no human ever has to endure and because of that
column3: iâ€™ve noticed myself trying to control the amount of future hurt in my romantic relationships. that comfort zone isnâ€™t always healthy in this case for i build walls. i am afraid to let others in. i am familiar with relying on myself and myself alone
column4: because i can control my actions.

column2: i deny myself the opportunity to let someone love me. that is if they want to. if i continue sitting in this comfort zone
column3: inside the walls i built around my heart
column4: iâ€™ll never know if a significant other is worthy of working through that for. more importantly
column5: iâ€™ll never feel a genuine connection that i know i deserve. during this full-moon energy and scorpio season
column6: i hope i can start to release some of that attachment to the identity of someone who has always been hurt by others because i trust there will be someone one day who wonâ€™t.

column1: 273416;instagram;2018-10-25 20:42:34;FALSE;"statistics show that 1 in 3 (!) women experienced trauma in her life. of any kind. and that's just statistics. with #metoo we have all seen that this number might be a lot higher even.

it is probably no surprise that being traumatized can have an impact on birth outcomes. women who survived trauma need the right kind of support from their birth support team. they need someone that takes time to truly listen. someone that supports them in whatever decision they make
today i learned important tools from sally kelly to be better able to give that kind of support to my clients who are survivors. i am so thankful to hold space for them
column2: actually for all of my clients
column3: so they can have control over their body and the birth of their baby. because that control belongs to them.

column1: 273441;instagram;2018-10-25 19:55:48;FALSE;"this week i stepped into room five at my local hospital's emergency room. the same room where my rape kit was performed on december 2
column3: nearly 11 months ago. 11 months ago i stepped into that room as a victim in shock
column4: having just been raped for a second time only 30 minutes ago. however
column5: i did not step in as a victim this past week. i stepped in as a survivor and as a crisis counselor and advocate for another survivor.

column2: i became a licensed sexual assault crisis counselor and advocate in my state following my assault.

column1: this was a particularly jarring and emotional experience
column2: sitting in the chair where my crisis counselor sat not that long ago. looking into the eyes of a victim wearing the same hospital gown and itchy socks that i was provided when i had my kit in that bed
column3: in that room. i felt everything she felt
column5: it enabled the ultimate empathetic response
column6: as i am sure not many survivors are given the opportunity to be in a situation so similar to the aftermath of their assault. and yes
column8: because i was blessed with the opportunity to be the eyes and ears for a victim in shock. i was blessed to be able to provide the service of support and advocacy that provided to me by my crisis counselor in the hospital. i was blessed to have grown strong enough in my healing to be able to step into that room and be there for another survivor.

column1: but that isn't to say that it wasn't extraordinarily difficult. with every step of the rape kit i was blindsided by thoughts of my own. with every nurse that came in i was terrified they might recognize me. when the victim tensed at the insertion of the speculum
column2: i did too. but i had to focus on the current survivor sitting in front of me experiencing those fears and pain in present time.

column1: i must provide the best support and advocacy because i know so intimately what it means to be let down by the system.
i had to be there for both of us.
there was a moment of inherent connection where she said she was so scared and couldn't get the flashes to stop and i simply said

column5: in using the verb of identity

column1: 273465;instagram;2018-10-25 02:20:21;FALSE;"thinking more lately of my time on this pale blue dot . my experiences . mistakes . lessons . accomplishments . the darkest and lightest moments . . . i have always believed in healing
column4: but maintaining a sense of peaceful groundedness has never been easy for me because of the level of inner turmoil i've had to manage (emotional and psychological)
column6: chronic illness and pain . . . but family and friends are there as i am for them . i have a small but exceptional support system . . . also: creativity! art
column8: writing has been my lifeline . i can't imagine living without numerous creative outlets . . . i am a social hermit . i am a square peg . i am soft and strong . resilient . ""too much"" for some . but i am me
column9: and i let my heart lead me . . . i've had some dark experiences that still shake me to my core
column10: and i've had some exquisitely beautiful moments that still move me deeply . . . my life has pretty much been driven by my desire to evolve . i like the idea of shedding unnecessary layers of self as we grow: a philosophy that led to the concept of
column12: 'vanety fabrick' . . . i am humbled by the strength i seem to have in reserve
column15: i am sometimes depleted . i've happily worked hard to exist in this world . to be positive energy and the best me i can be . not every moment of mine is stellar
column17: but i like who i am . i like what my spirit is doing with this beautiful mess called life . . . i am grateful for the time i've had here . i have learned so much through self study and through those of you in my life
column18: virtual or rl . . . though life has often been difficult
column19: i know i am privileged: i am grateful and never feel sorry for myself . when i go

column1: i've been following you on instagram for quite some time. and i didn't regret it. until today.
when you did that stupid press conference to ask for a ban on ceiling fans
when you made a video on donation
column2: saying that you want to donate your boobs because that's all you have.

it was all fine and funny until yesterday.
when you said that tanushree datta isn't straight and tried to rape you.
when you said that tanushree and  others like her are only using this movement to gain popularity
when you said that women of india are preying on indian men
column2: and the government needs to stop this movement from spreading any further.

column1: we as women lost all hopes.
as much as i am directly referring to you
column2: this also stands valid for the rest of your kind. all the aunties and friends and elder sisters who aren't supporting the movement. or even worse
column3: calling this movement a big propaganda.

column1: we as women don't fail when a man accuses us of fabrication.
we as women fail when other women questions our credibility.
i was told to not take you or your  interviews seriously
column2: but i don't know how can any woman not take another woman's words seriously when the later is clearly defaming a victim of sexual harassment and is clearly speaking in support of the harasser. i don't know how to ""not give a shit"" about you and your kind. i don't know how to ""not speak my heart out""
in fact we all know how much you like attention
column3: and tbh we all enjoy the stupid stuff you do in order to get it. but supporting a harasser is never an option. i repeat. never.

column1: 273649;instagram;2018-10-25 16:56:46;FALSE;"it's only in the human world we need things like ""women's rights"" it's only in the human world we assume a man is so much stronger than a woman other creatures don't think like that

column1: 273659;instagram;2018-10-25 17:01:37;FALSE;"i have had people in my life over and over again tell me in one way or another that i look 10 to 12 years older than what i am.

column2: a woman asked me that if i'm over 65 years old that i can go ahead and get special deals on yoga.

column1: i am 57 years old. as difficult as it sounds
column2: i am working on going within myself and feeling the pain which is like a heartache

column1: the pain that has to do with people always thinking i'm much older than i am. i'm looking at my ego
column2: about how i am buying into society that i have to look young.  i'm also looking at the grief deep inside of me of how that comment brings that up within me and being able to sit with this grief and really feel it in order to heal it. --------------------------------------------------------------------

column1: 273688;instagram;2018-10-25 16:34:09;FALSE;"{i am afraid. but i am doing it anyway.} there are different ways you can write about your life. you can wrap it in abstractions and hide it - or some of it - in the lines of a poem. you can take elements of it - either some or all - and weave them into an elaborate work of fiction (or ""autofiction"" as they might say). or you can go the non-fiction route. going that route
column3: demands one of the toughest decisions the writer has to face - namely
column4: do i write it all down and let the truth do what it needs to do
column5: or do i just give some of it away
column6: merely reveal the surface and hope that it is enough? both approaches are understandable and acceptable
column7: but from my experience the first route is the one the great writers tend to take. it may be too early to call emilie pine a great writer - notes to self is
column9: her first collection of essays - but the collection itself is great
column10: which bodes well. like any great collection of essays
column11: it does two things - it informs and it also teaches. when i say teaches
column12: i don't mean in a didactic sense. i mean that while reading these essays
column13: it's impossible to not wonder about yourself
column15: the way(s) in which you inhabit and navigate the world. this
column17: is how we truly learn. if your father was drinking his way to death

column7: jaimie lee curtis was awesome and i did like when all the other patients reacted to the presence of michaelâ€™s mask while he still stood in silence. the score is amazing and itâ€™s the reason i did this drawing. iâ€™ve been listening to it all day. but thatâ€™s it. for all itâ€™s flaws

she wanted to make something beautiful out of an issue that is so ugly and extends beyond hollywood. she said â€œhopefully this piece will inspire others to speak up and eventually put an end to this exploitative behavior.â€ charlotte graciously allowed me to wear the dress for this photo shoot. she added a paper petal with my experience of being sexually harassed and intimidated in the work place from dec 2015 to july 2018.

column2: my employer at the time minimized my experience by stating i was simply hypersensitive and overacted to the employee who stroked the back of my hair and made unwelcome and highly inappropriate comments to me and other women. iâ€™ve since moved on to work for another company.

column1: this photo shoot helped relieve some of my frustration and anger resulting from not being heard or taken seriously for years.

column2: i realized that perpetration has actually been in power for a long time.
i felt pretty defeated by this idea. it made me feel sad and a bit hopeless.
i sat with it and digested this idea and now i feel differently.

column1: while it's important to observe an idea like this it is also important to do the work to find the light in the situation. thatâ€™s something we humans have to do intentionally because our hardwiring is built to protect us from potential harm.

column2: here's where i am at with this.

column3: however we are woke af about it. way more woke than in the past. that's no small thing.

column1: there's also a lot of people fighting for good. as a collective we have a ton of power. we simply need to realize we have that power and press on.

column2: i know it feels like we are going back in time right now. this is true on a lot of levels. and if we take a look at history we will also find that the pendulum swings back and forth to create long term change. this is part of the process.

column1: that's not to say we shouldn't name it and get into action when we see things going backwards - we should do all of these things. that's how we continue to forge ahead.

column2: i would advocate for a wider perspective to help us not get so defeated. after all
column3: we have to stay engaged to create the change we wish to see.

column1: 273948;instagram;2018-10-25 13:45:37;FALSE;"à¤¦à¤¿à¤²à¥à¤²à¥€ à¤•à¥€ à¤—à¥à¤²à¤¾à¤¬à¥€ à¤§à¥‚à¤ª .. today  i read & heard two voices on #metoo. the first one was of @seemaskt on ig & the second one was by geetanjali prasad in the editorial pages of times of india during my flight to delhi. never really wrote about it earlier though i worked in a menâ€™s world all my life where women struggled hard to excel and not many could stop them in the world of voices. the power of the voices ruled the radio waves & it didnâ€™t matter whether they were male voices or female voices.

#metoo is beyond just me or you or him. it is a much larger issue of civil society understanding & accepting that â€œwork places must be made safe for women and that it should be the responsibility of the employer to protect women employees at every stepâ€.
it is for the parents to raise their girls to be fearless. it is for the men to understand that women are born equal.
geetanjali prasad remembered bhanwari devi and paid befitting tribute to a rural women who in her own way led the movement for gender equity in workplaces.
in 1997 the supreme court came out with the vishakha guidelines which evolved into the prevention of sexual harassment of women at workplace( posh)act in 2013.

i myself was custodian of this act in my own organisation. there used to be multitude of complaints and one was forever doing a tightrope walking while sitting on those committees to deliver justice. it was heart breaking sometimes to see a woman being sceptical about getting justice because she has been conditioned for years that no one will believe her.

but i know that even if we have taken tiny steps there is a lot of hope for a â€œjust societyâ€ because the civil society  today acknowledges and accepts the principle that women need a safe place of work. this in itself is a giant step in the history of women & work.
in a chhattisgarh twill/ herringbone weave saree. hand painted worli motifs bought from

column1: 273989;instagram;2018-10-25 13:23:17;FALSE;"i know what itâ€™s like to be afraid of the sunshine.
to always expect the pouring rain. to always think that it's too good to be true. convinced you'll be destined for pain. convinced that any ounce of happiness will be stolen from you.
i know what it's like to chase the light but never step out into it. to fear that if you let anyone in
column2: they'll reject you because of the memories you hold. to dismiss love or friendship because betrayal is the only thing you know that's been loyal to you.

column1: i know that trusting feels impossible.
i know that hope seems ridiculous.
i know that healing seems unreachable.
i know that love seems fabricated.
and it must start as a seed
column3: in the soil you find at rock bottom. buried deep in the ground so it can take root and penetrate the darkness. if you brave the seasons and nurture your seed with love
column5: that seed will break from its shell and sprout up into the light. and the thing you once were afraid of
column6: will now give you the gift you always prayed for; a new chance at life.
